post_text: Parents wanting their students to take the Gifted and Talented measurement test can print the permission form off of the school website, sign, and return to Mrs. Kunsman at the high school. This can be sent through email by simply taking a photo of the signed form and attaching it to an email to nkunsman@gorepublicschools.org. Testing will be done during the week of September 14-18. No testing will be done after that date for this academic year. Deadline to submit permission forms is September 11, 2020.

Students' that will be going virtual will have a designated pick up area at the Elementary for breakfast and lunches. The area will be at the awning in the pick up line starting at 10:30AM daily. post_text: Reopening Update: Gore Public Schools will follow all CDC, state, and Oklahoma State Department of Education guidelines for opening. The first day of school for students will be Thursday, August 27th. Please refer to the school website for the entire school calendar on the main page, under the latest news link. Specifics on reopening will be posted on the school website and Facebook by August 15th, when we have the most current CDC and state guidelines. The option for Gore students to go virtual will be available, and the specifics on this option will be released by August 15th.

post_text:
Oklahoma's Promise offers qualified Oklahoma students an opportunity to earn a scholarship for college tuition. Students completing the 10th grade MUST apply before the June 30th application deadline at the end of their sophomore year.

REQUIREMENTS
Must be an Oklahoma resident.
Must enroll in the 8th, 9th or 10th grade.
The parents' federal adjusted gross income must not exceed $55K per year.
Special income provisions may apply to:

Children adopted from certain court-ordered custody and children in the custody of court-appointed legal guardians.
Families receiving Social Security disability and death benefits.
We have many eligible students who miss the deadline of June 30th of their sophomore year. Do not delay and apply now! To apply go to www.okpromise.org.

--
Carmella McFarland, M.Ed.
Counselor
Gore Public Schools
918-489-5587 ext 5

There was a FB post linking to a donation site. This site asks for donations for Gore Elementary basketball uniforms. In the description there are statements that are not true or even close to being accurate.

Thank you for your support of Gore Schools.

McCrary, GPS Supt.

post_text:
Our 2nd annual Challenge Day event will be held for our high school students on Tuesday, December 17th, and we are once again looking for volunteers. Last year‚Äôs program was a rewarding experience that had a positive impact on all who were involved.

Challenge Days are powerful, high-energy programs in which youth and adult participants are guided through a series of experiential learning processes. The overall goals of the program are to increase personal power and self-esteem, to shift dangerous peer pressure to positive peer support and to eliminate the acceptability of teasing, violence and all forms of oppression. Challenge Day programs are designed to unite the members of the school and/or community and to empower them to carry the themes of the program back to the greater school population.

If you are interested in volunteering, please contact Ms. Murray at 918-489-5587 ext. 5 or murrayc@gorepublicschools.org. For more information regarding Challenge Day visit www.challengeday.org.

--
Carmella Murray M.Ed.
Counselor
Gore Public Schools
918-489-5587 ext 5

post_text: The Tulsa University invited Gore 5th grade students and teachers to come out to TU Basketball's Blackboards & Backboards Education Day for a day of learning and great basketball! Students enjoyed free tickets to the men's basketball game at noon and the school was treated to complimentary bus transportation. Students participated in an educational tour of the campus provided by TU ambassadors. Then many education groups had booths set up for students to visit which included Cherokee Nation, Tulsa County Library, the Tulsa Zoo, and many others. Students received a TU wristbands, education booklet, and bookmarks. One student, Rhylan Johnson, stated, he could see himself going to TU in the future. This was a wonderful opportunity for students to start planning for their futures.

post_text: 3rd through 5th grade Gore Elementary students recently participated in an illustration competition for a ticket to see a play at the Tulsa Performing Arts Center on Friday! Five winners from each grade were selected to go see the play Miss Nelson Has A Field Day at the Tulsa Performing Arts. Teachers read the story to the students, then the students were tasked to come up with their most creative illustration of the story. The winners, pictured here right to left, for the Miss Nelson Has a Field Day picture drawing contest are as follows; 3rd grade: Carl Mosier, Jayden Brimm, Brittan Phipps, Wyatt Thomas, Cruze Duke; 4th grade: Sarah Mannon, Evelette Cearley, Peyton Walker, Trenton Cunningham, Aubreyanna Fortenberry; 5th grade: River Shoemake, Sophie O‚ÄôConnor, Haley Thomas, Baylee Gates, and Dane Gates.

post_text:
The Cherokee Nation Foundation and The Princeton Review have partnered together to offer a free, 6-week ACT prep class to high school juniors and seniors who are citizens of Cherokee Nation. (Lower grades are welcome if space is available AND if they have taken Algebra 1 and are enrolled in Geometry.) This class is free of charge to you but normally costs over $600. You will be provided with materials that you will need to bring to each class, as well as receive homework assignments you will need to complete between classes. You are required to register for the upcoming National ACT and agree to be on time and stay for the duration of each class meeting. If a student is not a citizen of a federally recognized tribe, the cost of the class is $150.



Forms can be picked up in the counselor's office. Return completed forms to Jennifer Sandoval NO LATER THAN September 13 Email: j.sandoval@cherokeenationfoundation.org Fax: 918-207-0951

Please see the school counselor Mrs. Carmella Murray for more information!
